<h2>Coverage for Digital Nomads and Remote Workers</h2>

<p>Since Spain introduced its digital nomad visa (Ley de Startups) in 2023, Mallorca has become an increasingly popular base for remote workers from around the world. The digital nomad visa requires applicants to hold private health insurance in Spain, and there are specific considerations for this group:</p>

<h3>Key Requirements for Digital Nomad Visa Insurance</h3>
<ul>
  <li>The insurance must be provided by a company authorized to operate in Spain</li>
  <li>Coverage must be comprehensive and without copayments (<em>sin copago</em>)</li>
  <li>The policy must cover the full duration of your visa</li>
  <li>There should be no exclusions or limitations that would leave gaps in coverage</li>
  <li>International travel insurance or policies from your home country are generally NOT accepted</li>
</ul>

<h3>Best Options for Digital Nomads</h3>
<p>Digital nomads should consider providers that offer flexibility in contract terms, good telemedicine services (essential for remote workers), and ideally some level of international coverage for when you travel. Sanitas and Cigna are particularly popular among digital nomads due to their strong digital platforms, telemedicine options, and English-language support. Asisa is also a solid choice for those seeking the most competitive pricing.</p>

<p>If you''re a digital nomad who splits time between Mallorca and other countries, consider Cigna''s international plans or supplementing a local Spanish policy with travel insurance for periods spent abroad. Remember that most standard Spanish health insurance policies only cover you within Spain.</p>

<h2>Maternity and Fertility Coverage</h2>

<p>For expats planning to start or grow their families in Mallorca, understanding maternity and fertility coverage is essential. There are significant differences between providers:</p>

<h3>Public System Maternity Coverage</h3>
<p>If you''re eligible for public healthcare, maternity care is comprehensive and free, including prenatal checkups, ultrasounds, blood tests, hospital delivery (typically at Son Espases or Son Llatzer in Mallorca), postnatal care, and breastfeeding support. Spain''s public maternity care is of very high quality, though you may have limited choice of hospital and obstetrician.</p>

<h3>Private Insurance Maternity Coverage</h3>
<p>Most private insurers impose a <strong>waiting period of 8-12 months</strong> before maternity benefits activate. This means if you''re already pregnant or planning to conceive within the first year, you may need to rely on the public system for this specific care. Key differences between providers:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Sanitas:</strong> 8-month waiting period. Covers prenatal care, hospital delivery (private room), epidural, C-section, postnatal follow-up. Does not typically cover fertility treatments on standard plans.</li>
  <li><strong>Asisa:</strong> 8-month waiting period. Similar coverage to Sanitas. Some plans include basic fertility support after longer waiting periods.</li>
  <li><strong>Adeslas:</strong> 8-month waiting period on most plans. Comprehensive maternity package including private room, neonatology if needed. Fertility coverage available on premium plans.</li>
  <li><strong>DKV:</strong> 10-month waiting period. Covers standard maternity. Mental health support during and after pregnancy is a strength.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Fertility Treatments</h3>
<p>IVF and fertility treatments are available privately in Mallorca with several reputable clinics. Coverage through standard health insurance is limited. The public system covers some fertility treatments with strict criteria (age limits, number of attempts). Private insurance fertility riders or standalone fertility plans are available from some providers but tend to be expensive (adding &euro;50-100+ per month). Many expats choose to self-pay for fertility treatments, with IVF cycles in Mallorca costing approximately &euro;4,000-&euro;7,000 per cycle at private clinics.</p>

<h2>Mental Health Coverage Across Providers</h2>

<p>Mental health support is increasingly important for expats, who may face challenges with cultural adjustment, isolation, and the stress of navigating life in a new country. Coverage varies significantly between providers:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Public system:</strong> Covers psychiatry and some psychology through the SNS, but waiting times for mental health specialists in the Balearic Islands can be 2-6 months. Sessions are typically limited in number and conducted in Spanish or Catalan.</li>
  <li><strong>Sanitas:</strong> Offers psychology sessions (typically 15-20 per year on full coverage plans) and psychiatric care. Telemedicine mental health consultations available through their Blua app.</li>
  <li><strong>DKV:</strong> Generally the strongest mental health coverage among Spanish insurers. Offers more psychology sessions per year and has specific wellness and prevention programs.</li>
  <li><strong>Asisa and Adeslas:</strong> Standard psychology and psychiatry coverage. Session limits vary by plan (typically 15-25 per year).</li>
  <li><strong>Cigna:</strong> Good mental health coverage, especially on international plans. 24/7 support lines available in English.</li>
</ul>

<p>If mental health coverage is a priority, ask specifically about the number of psychology sessions included per year, whether telemedicine therapy is available, and whether the provider has English-speaking therapists in their network in Mallorca.</p>

<h2>Dental Insurance Add-Ons</h2>

<p>Dental care is generally NOT included in Spain''s public healthcare system (except for extractions in emergencies and children''s basic dental care). Most private health insurance policies include only basic dental coverage (annual checkup, one cleaning). For comprehensive dental care, you''ll need a dental add-on or standalone dental insurance:</p>

