<h2>Pre-Existing Condition Policies</h2>

<p>Understanding how Spanish insurers handle pre-existing conditions is crucial for many expats. Here''s what you need to know:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Declaration requirement:</strong> All Spanish insurers require you to complete a health questionnaire (<em>cuestionario de salud</em>) when applying. You must honestly declare all pre-existing conditions, ongoing treatments, and relevant medical history. Failure to declare can result in claim denials or policy cancellation.</li>
  <li><strong>Waiting periods:</strong> Most conditions are subject to waiting periods, typically 3-6 months for minor conditions and 8-12 months for more significant ones. During this period, treatment related to the pre-existing condition will not be covered.</li>
  <li><strong>Exclusions:</strong> Some conditions may be permanently excluded from coverage, especially if they require expensive ongoing treatment. The insurer will specify any exclusions in writing before you sign the contract.</li>
  <li><strong>Surcharges:</strong> In some cases, the insurer may offer coverage for a pre-existing condition but at an additional premium surcharge.</li>
  <li><strong>Guaranteed renewal:</strong> Once accepted, Spanish health insurers generally cannot cancel your policy or exclude conditions that develop after you''ve been insured. This is an important consumer protection under Spanish insurance law.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Tip:</strong> Asisa is often considered the most flexible provider regarding pre-existing conditions, while Sanitas and Adeslas may be stricter in their underwriting. If you have significant pre-existing conditions, work with an insurance broker who can negotiate with multiple providers on your behalf.</p>

<h2>How to File a Claim in Spain: Step by Step</h2>

<p>Filing a health insurance claim in Spain depends on whether you use providers within your insurer''s network (<em>cuadro m&eacute;dico</em>) or seek care outside the network:</p>

<h3>In-Network Care (Most Common)</h3>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Find a provider:</strong> Use your insurer''s app or website to find an in-network doctor, specialist, or clinic. Most insurers have search tools filtered by location, specialty, and language.</li>
  <li><strong>Book an appointment:</strong> Call the provider directly, use the insurer''s app, or call the insurer''s appointment booking line. Many insurers now offer online booking.</li>
  <li><strong>Attend your appointment:</strong> Present your insurance card and ID at the clinic. For copago plans, you''ll pay the copayment at the time of service. For full-coverage plans, there is usually nothing to pay.</li>
  <li><strong>Authorization for procedures:</strong> Some treatments, surgeries, and diagnostic tests require prior authorization (<em>autorizaci&oacute;n previa</em>) from the insurer. Your doctor will typically handle this, but it may take 24-72 hours for approval.</li>
  <li><strong>No claim filing needed:</strong> For in-network care, the provider bills the insurer directly. You don''t need to file a claim or submit receipts.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Out-of-Network or Reimbursement Claims</h3>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Pay upfront:</strong> Pay the full cost of the medical service at the time of treatment.</li>
  <li><strong>Collect documentation:</strong> Obtain an official invoice (<em>factura</em>) with the provider''s tax ID (NIF/CIF), a detailed description of the services received, and any medical reports.</li>
  <li><strong>Submit the claim:</strong> Most insurers allow claims submission through their app or online portal. You can also submit by email or post. Include the invoice, medical reports, and your policy details.</li>
  <li><strong>Wait for processing:</strong> Reimbursement typically takes 2-6 weeks. The amount reimbursed depends on your policy terms and may not cover 100% of out-of-network charges.</li>
  <li><strong>Follow up if needed:</strong> If you haven''t received reimbursement within the expected timeframe, contact customer service with your claim reference number.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Emergency Situations</h3>
<p>In a genuine emergency, go directly to the nearest hospital emergency department (<em>urgencias</em>), whether public or private. All insurers cover emergency care, and you should not delay treatment to check network status. Contact your insurer within 24-72 hours of an emergency admission to register the claim.</p>

<h2>Decision Flowchart: Which Insurance Do You Need?</h2>

<p>Your ideal health insurance setup in Mallorca depends on your specific situation. Here''s a practical guide based on residency type:</p>

<h3>EU Citizen Working in Spain (Employed)</h3>
<p>You''re covered by the public system through your social security contributions. Consider adding private insurance (&euro;50-120/month) for faster access and English-speaking doctors. Your employer may offer group private insurance as a benefit.</p>

<h3>EU Citizen Working in Spain (Aut&oacute;nomo/Self-Employed)</h3>
<p>You''re covered by the public system through your aut&oacute;nomo social security contributions. Private insurance is optional but popular. Many aut&oacute;nomos choose a basic copago plan to supplement the public system.</p>

<h3>EU Citizen - Retiree</h3>
<p>Apply for an S1 form from your home country for full public healthcare access. Many retirees add a basic private plan for convenience. See our <a href="/blog/health-insurance-over-65-mallorca">health insurance for over 65s in Mallorca guide</a>.</p>

<h3>Non-EU Citizen on Non-Lucrative Visa</h3>
<p>Private health insurance without copayments is mandatory for your visa application. You cannot rely on the public system. Budget &euro;80-200/month depending on age. After one year of residency, you may become eligible for the public system through <em>convenio especial</em>.</p>

<h3>Digital Nomad Visa Holder</h3>
<p>Private health insurance from a Spanish-authorized company is mandatory. Must be comprehensive and without copayments. Budget &euro;70-150/month. Sanitas and Cigna are popular choices.</p>

<h3>Non-EU Retiree</h3>
<p>Private insurance is typically required for residency. No reciprocal healthcare agreements (for most non-EU countries). Consider international insurers (Cigna Global, Bupa Global) or Spanish providers accepting seniors. Budget &euro;200-500+/month depending on age and health.</p>

<h3>UK Citizen (Post-Brexit)</h3>
<p>If you were registered as a resident in Spain before December 31, 2020, you retain healthcare rights under the Withdrawal Agreement. New arrivals must obtain private insurance for residency applications, similar to other non-EU citizens. UK GHIC provides emergency coverage during short visits. UK retirees may still be eligible for S1 form coverage.</p>

<h2>Insurance for Visitors and Tourists</h2>

<p>If you''re visiting Mallorca rather than residing here, your insurance options differ:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>EHIC/GHIC (European Health Insurance Card / Global Health Insurance Card):</strong> EU/EEA citizens and UK citizens should carry this card, which provides access to emergency and medically necessary treatment at public healthcare facilities on the same terms as Spanish residents. It does NOT cover private healthcare, repatriation, or non-emergency treatment.</li>
  <li><strong>Travel insurance:</strong> All visitors should consider travel insurance that includes medical coverage, emergency repatriation, and medical evacuation. This is especially important for non-EU visitors who don''t have EHIC rights. Look for policies covering at least &euro;100,000 in medical expenses.</li>
  <li><strong>Credit card travel insurance:</strong> Some premium credit cards include travel insurance as a benefit. Check the terms carefully, as coverage limits, exclusions, and claim processes vary widely.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Switching Between Insurance Providers</h2>

<p>If you''re unhappy with your current insurer or find a better deal, switching is straightforward in Spain:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Most health insurance contracts in Spain are annual, automatically renewing</li>
  <li>To cancel, you must provide written notice (typically 30 days before the renewal date, though some policies require 60 days)</li>
  <li>When switching, ensure there is no gap in coverage between the old and new policies</li>
  <li>Be aware that switching to a new insurer means new waiting periods for pre-existing conditions may apply</li>
  <li>Your claims history with the previous insurer does not transfer, but you also won''t be penalized for past claims</li>
  <li>Consider timing your switch to coincide with your policy renewal date to avoid potential penalties</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>

<h3>Do I need health insurance to get residency in Mallorca?</h3>
<p>It depends on your residency type and nationality. Non-EU citizens applying for visas such as the non-lucrative visa, digital nomad visa, or student visa must show proof of comprehensive private health insurance without copayments as part of their application. EU citizens can rely on their EHIC temporarily or demonstrate they will be covered through employment. Retirees from EU countries can use their S1 form. In practice, having health insurance is essential for all residents, even if it''s not a formal requirement for your specific residency category.</p>

<h3>How much does health insurance cost in Mallorca per month?</h3>
<p>Monthly costs for private health insurance in Mallorca range from approximately &euro;35-55 for a basic copago plan for someone in their 20s, up to &euro;300-600+ for comprehensive full-coverage plans for those over 65. The average expat in their 30s-40s typically pays &euro;80-150 per month for a comprehensive plan without copayments. Factors affecting price include your age, chosen provider, coverage level (copago vs. full coverage), and any add-ons like dental or maternity coverage. Always request quotes from multiple providers to compare.</p>

<h3>Can I use my European Health Insurance Card (EHIC) in Mallorca?</h3>
<p>Yes, if you hold a valid EHIC (or UK GHIC), you can access medically necessary treatment at public healthcare facilities in Mallorca on the same terms as Spanish nationals. This covers emergency treatment, necessary ongoing treatment for pre-existing conditions, and routine maternity care during a temporary stay. However, the EHIC does not cover private healthcare, non-emergency treatment if you are a resident, dental care (beyond emergencies), repatriation, or medical evacuation. It is designed for temporary stays, not for residents. If you''re moving to Mallorca permanently, you''ll need to arrange proper resident coverage.</p>

<h3>What does private health insurance typically NOT cover in Spain?</h3>
<p>Even comprehensive private health insurance in Spain typically excludes or limits certain types of care. Common exclusions include: cosmetic and elective surgery (procedures not deemed medically necessary), experimental treatments and clinical trials, self-inflicted injuries, injuries from extreme sports (unless a rider is added), pre-existing conditions during waiting periods, fertility treatments (unless specifically included), most dental implants and orthodontics (unless a dental rider is added), long-term nursing home care, and treatment related to substance abuse. Always read the policy exclusions carefully before signing, and ask your broker about any specific treatments or conditions you''re concerned about.</p>

<h3>Is there an age limit for getting private health insurance in Mallorca?</h3>
<p>Yes, most Spanish private health insurers impose maximum entry ages. Sanitas typically accepts new clients up to age 69-70. Asisa has a maximum entry age of around 65-69 depending on the plan. Adeslas generally accepts new clients up to age 65. DKV has varying limits, usually around 65-70. If you''re over 65, options become more limited and expensive. International health insurers like Cigna Global, Bupa Global, and Allianz Care may accept older applicants but at significantly higher premiums. See our detailed <a href="/blog/health-insurance-over-65-mallorca">guide to health insurance for over 65s in Mallorca</a> for specific guidance.</p>

<h3>Can I get health insurance in Mallorca if I have pre-existing conditions?</h3>
<p>Yes, but with certain limitations. Spanish insurers require you to declare all pre-existing conditions on a health questionnaire. Depending on the severity and cost of the condition, the insurer may: accept you with standard waiting periods (3-12 months during which the condition is not covered), accept you with the condition permanently excluded, accept you with a premium surcharge, or in rare cases decline the application. Asisa is generally considered the most flexible provider for pre-existing conditions. Working with an experienced insurance broker who can submit your application to multiple providers simultaneously is highly recommended if you have significant pre-existing conditions.</p>

<h3>How do I access emergency healthcare in Mallorca?</h3>
<p>In a medical emergency in Mallorca, call 112 (the pan-European emergency number) for an ambulance. You can go directly to the emergency department (<em>urgencias</em>) of any hospital. The main public hospitals with 24/7 emergency departments are Hospital Universitari Son Espases and Hospital Son Llatzer in Palma, Hospital de Manacor in the east, and Hospital Comarcal d''Inca in the north. Private hospitals with emergency departments include Clinica Rotger, Hospital Juaneda Miramar, and Clinica Juaneda. If you have private insurance, you can go to either public or private emergency rooms. Notify your insurer within 24-72 hours of any emergency admission. Emergency care will always be provided regardless of your insurance status.</p>

<h3>Should I use a broker or buy health insurance directly in Mallorca?</h3>
<p>Both options are valid, and the best choice depends on your situation. Using an insurance broker is recommended if you have pre-existing conditions (brokers can negotiate with multiple providers), if you''re new to the Spanish insurance market and want guidance, if you don''t speak Spanish, or if you want to compare multiple quotes without contacting each insurer individually. Brokers in Spain are typically paid by commission from the insurer, so their service is free to you and does not increase your premium. Buying directly is fine if you know exactly what you want, have no pre-existing conditions, and are comfortable navigating the application process. Many insurers like Sanitas have dedicated English-speaking sales teams for direct purchases.</p>

<h3>Does my Spanish health insurance cover me when traveling outside Mallorca?</h3>
<p>Most standard Spanish private health insurance policies cover you throughout Spain, not just in Mallorca. However, coverage outside of Spain is generally limited to emergencies during temporary travel (typically up to 30-90 days, depending on the policy). If you travel frequently outside Spain, consider supplementing your Spanish policy with travel insurance, or choose an international health insurance plan from providers like Cigna or Bupa that provides broader geographic coverage. If you have public healthcare (SNS), you can request a European Health Insurance Card (TSE in Spanish) that covers you for necessary treatment in other EU/EEA countries during temporary stays.</p>

<h3>What is the difference between copago and full coverage (sin copago) health insurance in Spain?</h3>
<p>Copago plans have lower monthly premiums but require you to pay a small fee (copayment) each time you use a medical service. Typical copayments range from &euro;3-5 for a GP visit, &euro;5-15 for a specialist, &euro;10-20 for diagnostic tests, and &euro;50-150 for hospital admission. Full coverage plans (<em>sin copago</em> or <em>cuadro m&eacute;dico completo</em>) have higher monthly premiums but no additional charges when you access care. For visa applications in Spain, authorities typically require full-coverage plans without copayments. If you use medical services frequently, a full-coverage plan may be more economical despite the higher monthly cost. If you rarely see doctors and mainly want coverage for emergencies, a copago plan can save money.</p>

